	<item>
		<title>How to Do a PPC Keyword Gap Analysis to Find New Opportunities</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ppc-keyword-gap-analysis</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Michelle Morgan]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 05 May 2025 12:30:49 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Keyword Research & Tools]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=91112</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Want to expand your PPC keyword list while stealing market share from your competitors? Find out how a keyword gap analysis can help.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ppc-keyword-gap-analysis">How to Do a PPC Keyword Gap Analysis to Find New Opportunities</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In the world of online marketing, a keyword gap analysis is most associated with SEO, where a company will compare the keywords their website is ranking for against their competitors‚Äô keywords to identify any areas that the competitor ranks for that they don‚Äôt. The goal is to find keywords their competitors are outperforming them for and develop a strategy to catch up.</p>
<p>Aside from the word ‚Äúranking‚Äù and assuming it also translates to ‚Äúperformance,‚Äù there‚Äôs nothing to say that this process couldn‚Äôt be applicable to paid media campaigns as well. Or that only keywords your competitors are bidding on are valuable.</p>
<p>In this article, I want to talk about how we can use (mostly free) tools to do a similar process of keyword discovery for paid search campaigns and discuss why you may want to do so.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#why-do-a-keyword-gap-analysis-for-ppc">Why do a keyword gap analysis for PPC</a></li>
<li><a href="#how-to-do-a-keyword-gap-analysis-for-google-ads">How to do a keyword gap analysis for Google Ads</a>
<ol>
<li><a href="#take-stock-of-your-existing-keywords">Take stock of your existing keywords</a></li>
<li><a href="#gather-your-competitors">Gather your competitors</a></li>
<li><a href="#scan-your-competitors-sites">Scan your competitors‚Äô sites</a></li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><a href="#ppc-keyword-gap-analysis-example">PPC keyword gap analysis example</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="why-do-a-keyword-gap-analysis-for-ppc"></div>
<h2>Why do a keyword gap analysis for PPC?</h2>
<p>Whether you‚Äôre trying to find new keywords through your own search terms or are <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/11/09/competitor-keywords">looking at where competitors are bidding</a>, keyword discovery is a great way to ensure your paid search accounts are alive and evolving. Odds are that the initial <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2013/11/21/ppc-keyword-research-guide">keyword research</a> you did when you launched your campaigns is still applicable. But over time, things change.</p>
<p>Google continues to assert that 15% of queries every day are brand new, never before seen by their system.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/new-queries-on-google-png.webp" alt="google says 15% of queries are new each day" width="1436" height="322" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91141" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/new-queries-on-google-png.webp 1436w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/new-queries-on-google-1280x287.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/new-queries-on-google-980x220.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/new-queries-on-google-480x108.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1436px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Whether you leverage your search terms to see how queries evolve or if you piggyback off the work your competitors are doing, this type of gap analysis can ensure that you‚Äôre moving with your customer base and not staying stagnant while everyone leaves you behind.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f440.png" alt="üëÄ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want a quick look at how your Google Ads are doing?</strong> Try our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader">Free Google Ads Performance Grader</a> for an instant audit!</p>
<div id="how-to-do-a-keyword-gap-analysis-for-google-ads"></div>
<h2>How to do a keyword gap analysis to improve PPC campaigns: Step by step</h2>
<p>Follow these steps to perform a keyword gap analysis you can use to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/adwords-optimization">optimize your search campaigns</a>.</p>
<div id="take-stock-of-your-existing-keywords"></div>
<h3>1. Take stock of your existing keywords</h3>
<p>We‚Äôll get to your competitors in a minute, but the first place I always encourage advertisers to look for new keywords is in their Search Terms Report.</p>
<p>In Google Ads, this is under the Insights and Reports section of the interface, and all the terms here are queries you‚Äôre already showing up for.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/google-ads-search-terms-report-insights-png.webp" alt="search terms report in google ads" width="361" height="800" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91154" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/google-ads-search-terms-report-insights-png.webp 361w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/google-ads-search-terms-report-insights-135x300.webp 135w" sizes="(max-width: 361px) 100vw, 361px" /></p>
<p>Once you‚Äôre there, there‚Äôs a simple filter that will help you find only net new terms to your account. Either navigate to the Attributes dropdown or search for ‚ÄúAdd‚Äù in the filters like I did in the image above, and choose the Added/Excluded option from the dropdown.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/add-terms-search-terms-report-png.webp" alt="add/excluded filter in search terms report" width="824" height="282" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91143" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/add-terms-search-terms-report-png.webp 824w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/add-terms-search-terms-report-480x164.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 824px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>From there, check the box next to None. This will show you only search terms that your ads are showing for that you‚Äôve not added as keywords already or that aren‚Äôt added as negative keywords.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/search-terms-report-attributes-added-excluded-png.webp" alt="how to filter for excluded search terms" width="508" height="646" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91144" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/search-terms-report-attributes-added-excluded-png.webp 508w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/search-terms-report-attributes-added-excluded-480x610.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 508px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The benefit to this is that you‚Äôre likely finding new variants of relevant terms that your customers are actively searching for. They‚Äôre likely a good fit for your business (assuming you do regular <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/06/06/negative-keyword-guide">negative keyword</a> reviews), and they are guaranteed to have search volume since you‚Äôre already seeing it in your account.</p>
<p>Additionally, although Google always suggests getting rid of terms that are ‚Äúduplicates,‚Äù even though they‚Äôre not identical, they still reward advertisers for having the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/exact-match">Exact match</a> to a query in the account. It‚Äôs laid out in their prioritization documents. If a query is the exact same as a keyword in your account and another is close, but not identical, then the exact version will have a higher Ad Rank and have a better chance of matching.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/top-priority-to-low-priority-keywords-png.webp" alt="keywords from top to lowest priority" width="1620" height="910" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91145" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/top-priority-to-low-priority-keywords-png.webp 1620w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/top-priority-to-low-priority-keywords-1280x719.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/top-priority-to-low-priority-keywords-980x550.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/top-priority-to-low-priority-keywords-480x270.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1620px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f50e.png" alt="üîé" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Need help finding the right keywords for your campaigns?</strong> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keywords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Keywords_KWTool">Try our Free Keyword Tool!</a></p>
<div id="gather-your-competitors"></div>
<h3>2. Gather your competitors</h3>
<p>The first stage in this process is to <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-find-your-competitors/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">get a list of competitors</a> you want to use to review for gaps. There are two different types of competitors I want you to think about for this exercise.</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Traditional competitors: </strong>These are companies that do the same things you do, and you likely compete directly for the same customers. Think large brands like Dunkin‚Äô and Starbucks, or smaller scale like one roofing company vs another.</li>
<li><strong>Active advertisers: </strong>These are the companies that are bidding on your keywords. For this, conduct a simple search with your existing keywords and see who comes up. These are folks that you are literally competing with in search, even if they don‚Äôt do the same things you do.</li>
</ol>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/who-to-include-in-ppc-keyword-gap-analysis-png.webp" alt="who to include in ppc keyword gap analysis circle chart" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91146" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/who-to-include-in-ppc-keyword-gap-analysis-png.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/who-to-include-in-ppc-keyword-gap-analysis-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The reason we use both groups is because of the diagram above. There are some companies that are direct competitors and they aren‚Äôt bidding against you, others that aren‚Äôt really competitors but are bidding against you, and the group we‚Äôll likely learn the most from is the cross-section of the two: those who are your competitors and are bidding on your terms.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f575-fe0f-200d-2640-fe0f.png" alt="üïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want an even deeper look at what your competitors are doing?</strong> Free guide &gt;&gt; <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/how-to-spy-on-competitors?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_SpyOnCompetitors_Download">How to Spy on Your Competitors: 7 Ways to Become a Competitive Supersleuth</a></p>
<div id="scan-your-competitors-sites"></div>
<h3>3. Scan the websites</h3>
<p>Now that we have our list of competitors, we‚Äôre going to use their websites for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitors-ads">some light snooping</a>.</p>
<p>We‚Äôre going to use the Google Ads Keyword Planner and select the ‚ÄúStart with a Website‚Äù option and input each of the sites from the competitor.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-planner-scan-websites-for-keywords-png.webp" alt="scan websites for keywords in the google ads keyword planner" width="1666" height="649" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91148" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-planner-scan-websites-for-keywords-png.webp 1666w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-planner-scan-websites-for-keywords-1280x499.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-planner-scan-websites-for-keywords-980x382.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-planner-scan-websites-for-keywords-480x187.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1666px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The results listed will show all the keywords Google thinks the website is about. This can give you all sorts of ideas based just on the content of your competitor‚Äôs site.</p>
<p>The best part: there‚Äôs a column on the far right that will show you if you already have a keyword in your account or not. This is a very quick way for you to review a keyword for relevancy and then to easily check if you‚Äôve already been using it or if it‚Äôs a new term you can test out.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keywords-in-account-status-png.webp" alt="keywords in account in google ads keyword planner" width="1980" height="624" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91149" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keywords-in-account-status-png.webp 1980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keywords-in-account-status-1280x403.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keywords-in-account-status-980x309.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keywords-in-account-status-480x151.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1980px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>At times, a company‚Äôs entire website can be a bit broad. If you‚Äôre finding lots of irrelevant terms but you‚Äôre confident the company is relevant to your business, try using individual pages from the site rather than the whole site. If possible, even grab some of their <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/great-landing-pages">landing pages</a> and run those through the tool to see what you can come up with.</p>
<div id="ppc-keyword-gap-analysis-example"></div>
<h2>A PPC keyword gap analysis example</h2>
<p>While the Google Ads Keyword Planner can be a great tool for identifying new terms and easily comparing them to your accounts, I‚Äôm a really big fan of the functionality in some of the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/11/09/competitor-keywords">paid research tools</a> out there. One of my favorites is <a href="https://www.spyfu.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SpyFu</a>, but others have similar functionality.</p>
<p>With SpyFu, you can take all of your competitors (direct or indirect), put their websites into the tool, and see all sorts of information about their paid search campaigns.</p>
<p>Here are some of the data points you can see:</p>
<ul>
<li>Search terms their ads have shown for</li>
<li>Average ad budget</li>
<li>Number of active keywords</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Caveat before we go further: </strong>All of this is inferred data. SpuFu can‚Äôt actually know what a competitor&#8217;s keywords are or how much they spend. They can only see the search terms an advertiser showed up for and reverse engineer the number of active keywords and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-shared-budgets">ad budget</a> from there.</p>
<p>While this data isn‚Äôt perfect, there‚Äôs still plenty we can learn from it. So if you can accept this caveat, which you should, then keep reading.</p>
<p>Still here?</p>
<p>Great!</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs start by taking an example website, Lowes.com. (Yes, I‚Äôve been doing home improvement projects, so Lowe&#8217;s is top of mind.</p>
<p>If we input lowes.com into SpuFu, then navigate to the PPC Research section, then choose PPC Keywords, we‚Äôll see a report that looks like this. It has the top performing PPC search queries that Lowes has been showing up for.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lowes-keywords-spyfu-png.webp" alt="lowes ppc keywords in spyfu" width="1999" height="1262" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91150" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lowes-keywords-spyfu-png.webp 1999w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lowes-keywords-spyfu-1280x808.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lowes-keywords-spyfu-980x619.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lowes-keywords-spyfu-480x303.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1999px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>As you can see, the report is truncated to only the top five terms since we‚Äôre in a free account, but if you were to pay for SpyFu, you‚Äôd see a lot more variants show up here.</p>
<p>Each of these terms could be a valuable keyword for you to target if you‚Äôre a competitor of Lowe&#8217;s and want to show up in the same SERPs that they are. A similar process can be done for all of your competitors to find the top terms they show up for and try to take some new themes for yourself.</p>
<p>That said, my favorite report in SpyFu is the Kombat report. On this tab, you can input multiple competitors, then see how their search term coverage overlaps in a Venn Diagram.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/spyfu-kombat-report-png.webp" alt="spyfu kombat report for lowes" width="1999" height="884" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91151" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/spyfu-kombat-report-png.webp 1999w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/spyfu-kombat-report-1280x566.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/spyfu-kombat-report-980x433.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/spyfu-kombat-report-480x212.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1999px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Here, you can see Home Depot and Menards‚Äô search term coverage against Lowe&#8217;s. There‚Äôs a group of 118 ‚ÄúCore Keywords,‚Äù meaning all three brands bid on these terms.</p>
<p>But the gems come from seeing which terms either Home Depot or Menards bid on that Lowe&#8217;s doesn‚Äôt. Specifically, the ‚ÄúConsider Buying‚Äù section, in this instance with 70 keywords, shows the search terms Home Depot and Menards are showing for that Lowe&#8217;s isn‚Äôt.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-gap-on-spyfu-png.webp" alt="lowes keyword gap on spyfu" width="1846" height="524" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91152" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-gap-on-spyfu-png.webp 1846w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-gap-on-spyfu-1280x363.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-gap-on-spyfu-980x278.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/keyword-gap-on-spyfu-480x136.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 1846px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>In this instance, two competitors are showing for the above terms, while Lowe&#8217;s is left out. If you‚Äôre the Paid Search Manager for Lowe&#8217;s and you know you offer Owens Corning Duration Shingles, that might be a good term for you to look into.</p>
<p>Additionally, three of the five listed terms are for ‚Äúappliances‚Äù plus a city, state location. That could be an entire keyword theme Lowe&#8217;s should look into researching and building out to ensure they have coverage for folks looking for appliances in areas where they have stores.</p>
<p>Again, these are only the queries Home Depot and Menards are showing for, not the specific keywords, but they‚Äôre both onto something with the location terms, and it appears Lowe&#8217;s is being left out of that market conversation. Probably a good place to at least investigate and see if this should be added to their paid search coverage.</p>
<h2>Look for new opportunities with a PPC keyword gap analysis</h2>
<p>A keyword gap analysis can help you identify new areas for your search campaigns to reach potential customers based on what your competitors are doing. By following these simple steps, you can discover opportunities to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keyword-expansion">expand your keyword lists</a> and optimize your campaigns. And if you&#8217;d like to learn more about PPC, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-accurate-is-ai-for-ppc">see which AI tools have the most accurate information</a> (we tested it!)</p>
<p>Need help with your Google Ads? Reach out for a demo to see how we can help.</p>
